{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"रस\n    \n      Rasa\n      Sanskrit — \"essence, taste, emotional flavor of art\"\n      \n        In Indian aesthetics: the emotional juice that art evokes in a sensitive viewer —\n        a sahṛdaya, literally \"one who has heart.\" There are nine rasas: love, wonder,\n        courage, peace, humor, sadness, fury, fear, and disgust. Your game literally has a\n        taste model that learns what beauty means to each player.\n        The word is 4 letters. Easy to say in any language. Deeply meaningful.\n        \n        \"The aesthetic flavour that evokes an indescribable feeling —\n        relished by one who has heart.\"\n        — Natya Shastra, ~200 BCE","choice":"rasa","id":null,"timestamp":1773794122238}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"/|\\\n    \n      Awen\n      Welsh — \"flowing spirit\"\n      \n        From the Indo-European root meaning \"to blow.\" Same root as awel — breeze, wind.\n        The inspiration of the poets. The breath of the gods. The song of nature itself.\n        You're literally playing as wind carrying flame petals through evolving worlds.\n        The ancient druidic symbol /|\\ represents three rays of light converging.\n        \n        \"Aw\" means flowing. \"Wen\" means spirit, or a being.\n        Together: a flowing being. A spirit in motion.","choice":"awen","id":null,"timestamp":1773794122904}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"स्पन्द\n    \n      Spanda\n      Sanskrit — \"the divine creative pulse\"\n      \n        The subtle vibration of consciousness as it manifests into living form.\n        Not a gross movement — a tremor. The heartbeat before creation.\n        Music is vibration. Fractals are patterns from pulsation. Evolution is creative pulse.\n        The word literally means \"to move a little\" — the smallest motion that creates everything.\n        \n        \"This divine power is Spanda — the vibration of consciousness.\n        The creative impulse that makes the formless take form.\"\n        — Kashmir Śaivism, 9th century","choice":"spanda","id":null,"timestamp":1773794123471}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"/|\\\n    \n      Awen\n      Welsh — \"flowing spirit\"\n      \n        From the Indo-European root meaning \"to blow.\" Same root as awel — breeze, wind.\n        The inspiration of the poets. The breath of the gods. The song of nature itself.\n        You're literally playing as wind carrying flame petals through evolving worlds.\n        The ancient druidic symbol /|\\ represents three rays of light converging.\n        \n        \"Aw\" means flowing. \"Wen\" means spirit, or a being.\n        Together: a flowing being. A spirit in motion.","choice":"awen","id":null,"timestamp":1773794126721}
